<span class=title>   Re: Is the War with Iraq all about oil?</span><hr size=1> Well, considering the start of the Gulf War caused an economic recession in the US, and since as of this moment, a poor economy is the only thing that could hurt Bush's chances of being re-elected in 2004; I don't think ending the Gulf War is about oil.  Frankly, we can already buy all the oil we want from Iraq.  In fact, our demand for Iraqi oil has gone down in the last two years.<br>
<br>
I think this is a part of the War on Terror.  That's the main reason we must topple Saddam Hussein and run him, his sons, and his gang of Ba'athist murderers out of Baghdad. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 738<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/19/03 8:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=360.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Is the War with Iraq all about oil?</span><hr size=1> I'm somewhat stumped myself by the great urgency with which the Whitehouse seems to be pressing for war.  The inspectors haven't really found anything of great consequence minus a few empty warheads and Iraq hasn't been bullying it's neighbors so why the sudden cries for war?  This whole weapons of mass destruction bit just sounds like somekind of spin story that's hiding the true motives for the war.  I hope Gladimir is right in his assessment but I'm more cynical.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 77<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/19/03 11:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=360.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Is the War with Iraq all about oil?</span><hr size=1> I tend to be more skeptical as well, as I am with most power figures.  The main points I have are (a) the lack of an immediate threat; as long as the inspectors are there, no significant progress is going to be made and (b) the lack of international support.  I think at least one of these two conditions must be met before I can support any military action anywhere. <br>
<br>
Do I condone the actions of Saddam and his government?  By no means.  Would I shoot him if I had the chance?  Yes.  Do I think we should invade a country where many innocents will be killed without at least marginal international support?  No.  If the UN were to rule that he must abdicate or military action must be taken, I would be for it.  That's the purpose of the UN.<br>
<br>
My main concern is that even if we do go to war without support and win, we will lose a LOT of our political capital and hegemony throughout the world.  The cost and risks do not outweigh the potential gains.  In essence, we win the battle but at a horrible cost and we may lose the war.<br>
<br>
The main reasons for the war whether conscious or not, in my opinion, are (a) the people in the Bush administration want to be remembered in the history books, (b) they don't want to (or the American people to) focus on the economy, (c) they feel the need to impose democracy around the world (and yes, I have heard from reliable people that many in the Bush administration believe it is their duty to spread democracy; even if it means forcing it down peoples throats), and (d) they have been so caught up in the &quot;War on Terror&quot; that they feel it necessary.  <br>
<br>
My opinion is all of these are bad.  The War on Terror is not really a war.  When Bush said, &quot;America cannot survive another terrorist attack&quot; I was appauled.  Are the US people that weak?  The British took months of bombing of London by the Nazis in WWII, can't we at least do half that?  Yes, people are going to die due to terrorism.  Yes, we should make attempts to find culprits.  However, I think we are going the wrong route.  <br>
<br>
I think we need to use our resources and give like another Marshall Plan.  Sure, the Europeans may not appreciate it today.  But, they are not strapping on bombs and trying to kill the US.  As much as they talk, their dislike is not to the point where they are willing to kill.  Besides, in the future it can only mean more competition. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1845<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/20/03 4:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=360.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Is the War with Iraq all about oil?</span><hr size=1> Basically, Saddam put a hit out on George's Dad, Bush Sr.,<br>
